<br>
Stick to your guns.  People on this server are supposed to *at least* respect roleplay---however one chooses to do it. There are a lot more out there who support you than do not. And if someone becomes crabby or offended about your roleplay even after you explain yourself oocly to him/her, put them on /ignore. <br>
<br>
There are ooc situations where I step out of my roleplaying shoes for an incidence here or there. But otherwise, as far as grouping, etc, I do not.<br>
<br>
I have no problem with doing occasional ooc favors (or accepting them) for evil when someone is in a real bind. For instance, last night, my corpse was lost beyond recovery in Kael Drakkel behind a pack of angry red-con (to 42) giants that could SEE THROUGH invis. Don't ask how I ended up there *blush*. None of my fellow goody two-shoes companions had a chance of getting past them mean see-invis giants, and my corpse was *way* in there. Enter Zarsiss (I hope I spelled that right), vile, snarling Iksar monk. He and his shaman companion had been hunting somewhere else in Kael, and desperate, a guildmate of mine asked via ooc tells if he could possibly feign-death pull my corpse from the midst of the giants. He very kindly agreed and I had my corpse soon enough. After I got my corpse, then the animosity continued (vile, smelly, Iksar!). <br>
<br>
But I've also taken shit for refusing to rez a necromancer. Now, the guy asked me in character, and I refused in character. He got rather miffed that I wouldn't rez him, but he not once mentioned why it was so important to him. We were in Oasis, and he was probably only in his upper teens or so, so I didn't consider his situation dire.  I assumed he was bound in Freeport and just wanted to spare himself the run.  Later I found he was bound far off from his corpse. Now, if he had sent a quick OOC tell that he was bound in B.F.E. and rezzing him would be an act of kindness on my part, I, the player behind my character, would have rezzed him without a thought, where my character Isharra would not have. As a player, however, I know the mechanics of the game and how sometimes it is necessary to help a fellow player in times of need. After all, the player behind the evil avatar isn't evil... he or she just chose to play an evil character. <br>
<br>
I think it all comes down to whether people understand the difference between ooc and ic or not. Unfortunately, there are a lot of nonroleplayers on the server who just don't get it. Hopefully, the majority are roleplayers, though, and DO get it. So don't let those few instances get you down.  Keep ooc and ic separate, and you'll be fine.<br>
<br>
